1099301989593174018.text: 14/ and for all other cases, z is a non-integer between the next integer up from a perfect square and the next one:  m²+1 < z < (m + 1)², in which case ⌈√⌊z⌋ ⌉ = ⌈√z⌉  bc the ceiling of both is m+1. The book helped me realise this last case.pic.twitter.com/kaRDqtdhON

1099301987848339456.text:
13/ We can cover all cases of z like this (where m is an integer):
when z is an integer, ⌈√⌊z⌋ ⌉ = ⌈√z⌉  bc √⌊z⌋ = √z
when z is a non-integer whose floor is a perfect square: m² < z < m² + 1 then ⌈√⌊z⌋ ⌉ != ⌈√z⌉ bc √⌊z⌋ = m and  ⌈√z⌉ = m+1

1099301986451636225.text: 12/ I noticed early on that it's not equal if ⌊z⌋ is a perfect square bc the square roots of ⌊z⌋ and z can’t actually straddle a boundary bc they have to have the same integer part (bc the other thing I proved and having done this operation by hand countless times).

1099301984329297920.text: 11/ So ⌈√⌊z⌋ ⌉ != ⌈√z⌉  when ⌊z⌋ is a perfect square and z is not an integer. Cool. To finish the proof I’d have to prove I covered all cases of when ⌈x⌉ != ⌈y⌉.  But this madness. Where did my Saturday night go. There’s an easier way.

1099301982739750913.text:
10/ And since x can't be less than ⌊x⌋, we get
√⌊z⌋ =  ⌊√⌊z⌋⌋ < √z
The first part is saying √⌊z⌋ is an integer, which only happens if ⌊z⌋ is a perfect square. And since  ⌊√z⌋ < √z , z is not a perfect integer itself, so it's not an integer (just its floor is).

1099301981347147776.text:

√⌊z⌋ <= ⌊√z⌋ < √z 
We know from an earlier proof that ⌊√z⌋ =  ⌊√⌊z⌋⌋ so
 √⌊z⌋ <=  ⌊√⌊z⌋⌋ < √z

⌈√⌊z⌋ ⌉ != ⌈√z⌉ 
let x = √⌊z⌋  and y = √z
